<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVIES TO TAPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Dr. Giggles (HBO Sunday at 8 p.m.) stars "L.A. Law's" Larry Drake as a mental 
patient obsessed with surgery in this fast and frequently hilarious 1992 
collision of gore and gags. 
</P>
<P>
 America, America (AMC Monday at 6 and 11 p.m.): Elia Kazan drew from the 
experiences of his own uncle in this profound and exhilharating 19th-Century 
immigrant saga, made in 1963 and expressing passionately a love of this 
country. Stathis Giallelis stars. 
</P>
<P>
 Bonjour Tristesse (TNT Tuesday at 10:30 p.m.) is Otto Preminger's wise, 
elegant and underappreciated 1968 film of the Francoise Sagan novel centering 
on a willful teen-ager; Deborah Kerr, David Niven and Jean Seberg star. 
</P>
