<HEADLINE>
<P>
PALM LATITUDES: THE WORD; THE KARAOKE KRONICLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kit Roane 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Karaoke seems more popular than Prozac in Southern California these days. And 
that may not be a coincidence: "It's therapeutic," declares Dennis G. Snyder, a 
KJ -- karaoke jockey -- and publisher of the 11-month-old newsletter California 
Karaoke Scene. 
</P>
<P>
 With so many folks taking advantage of the carthartic effects of pretending to 
be Frank or Barry or Liza, Snyder says his publication is proof of the boom. In 
the first issue eight months ago, only 60 karaoke clubs were listed; the 
newsletter now includes more than 200. Snyder says he distributes 25,000 copies 
of his bimonthly newsletter at clubs and other outlets throughout Los Angeles 
and the Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 Snyder's newsletter offers more than just listings. It recently reported on 
two scalawags who had gone to great lengths to win their respective big-buck 
sing-along contests (Karaoke croon-offs now offer prizes as high as $1,000): 
One told his competitors that the night of the contest had been changed. 
Another used his universal remote control to change the key of some of his 
competitor's songs. Both were apprehended and reprimanded. We can only hope 
they were forced to listen to each other sing "Feelings." Kit Roane 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
