<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITICS' PICKS: 'I DON'T BUY KISSES ANYMORE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This irresistable little 1992 movie, beautifully directed by Robert 
Marcarelli, got lost in theatrical release but just might find new life on the 
tube. Jason Alexander (pictured) stars as a suburban Philadelphia store owner 
who always buys chocolate kisses at the end of the day before boarding a bus 
for home.He's a nice young Jewish man, some 30 pounds overweight, who still 
lives at home with his doting mother (Lainie Kazan) and bombastic grandfather 
(Lou Jacobi). One day he meets on the bus the woman (Nia Peeples, pictured) who 
could change his life. Jonnie Lindell's wonderfully warm script is a romantic 
comedy that shows how limiting our perceptions of each other and ourselves can 
be. -- (Cinemax Thursday at 2:30 p.m.) Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</TEXT>
