<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP WRESTLING; CALVARY CHAPEL QUALIFIES EIGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PETER BARZILAI and MICHAEL LAZARUS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Southern Section Masters' wrestling meet at Fountain Valley High Saturday 
was merely another stop for Santa Ana Calvary Chapel as it looks to win its 
second consecutive State title. 
</P>
<P>
 By qualifying a meet-high eight wrestlers for next weekend's State tournament 
at the University of Pacific in Stockton, the Eagles put themselves in an ideal 
position. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're definitely peaking right now," said Dane Valdez, who won the 125-pound 
title, beating Temecula Valley's Mark Perryman, 15-8. 
</P>
<P>
 Valdez was one of four Calvary Chapel wrestlers to win championships. Brother 
Shane Valdez won at 119 pounds, Joshua Holiday at 145, and Tim Bonebright at 
152. 
</P>
<P>
 Reuben De Leon of Ontario Chaffey prevented Joe Calavitta from winning another 
championship for the Eagles. De Leon defeated Calavitta, 11-4, at 103 pounds to 
earn his second consecutive Masters' title. 
</P>
<P>
 In one of the closest championship matches of the evening, Vincent Virgen of 
Buena Park beat Teak Sato of Orange El Modena, 12-8. Virgen was ranked second 
in Orange County this season, and Sato was second in the state last season. 
</P>
<P>
 Although Steven Abas of Moreno Valley Canyon Springs had to settle for third 
place at 112, he set a national record for takedowns in a season. Abas got his 
329th when he beat Lakewood's Brian Gilland. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Bell High, bolstered by five individual titles, won its second consecutive 
City Section crown with 185 1/2 points at Bell. 
</P>
<P>
 Jose Gonzalez (112 pounds), Ramsas Ochoa (145), Frank Ordorica (171), Jesus 
Orozco (189) and Adolfo Padilla (heavyweight) won for the Eagles. Orozco was 
voted the outstanding wrestler for the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
 Woodland Hills El Camino Real finished second with 163 points and won three 
titles: Andy Becker (103), Casey Lee (119) and Rick Ullman (152). Canoga Park 
finished third, winning two titles. 
</P>
<P>
 The winner in each weight class advances to the State tournament. PETER 
BARZILAI and MICHAEL LAZARUS 
</P>
</TEXT>
