<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 11; Column 5; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
119 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
'94 WINTER OLYMPICS / LILLEHAMMER; NOTEBOOK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROSS NEWHAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The dominant bobsledders of the last decade -- Gustav Weder of Switzerland I 
and Wolfgang Hoppe of Germany I -- were applying the heat as Harald Czudaj of 
Germany II took a slim lead into today's final two heats of the four-man 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
 The second-place Weder, 32, has already won the gold in two-man and won the 
gold in two-man and a bronze in four-man in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 The third-place Hoppe, 36, won silver in four-man in 1992, silver in both 
four-man and two-man in 1988, and gold in both four-man and two-man in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
 He has also won seven world bobsled titles, and still competes in motocross, a 
family tradition. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's where I get the necessary courage and feel for speed," he said. ROSS 
NEWHAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
