<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: PORT HUENEME; TEACHING ASSISTANTS FACE POSSIBLE LAYOFFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Teaching assistants at the Port Hueneme school district have been informed 
that they could be facing layoffs next year because of budget cuts. 
</P>
<P>
 School district administrators notified union representatives at a closed 
meeting on Thursday that the school board would consider a plan to lay off 11 
teaching assistants who work with disadvantaged children in three schools. 
</P>
<P>
 The possibility of layoffs is due to reductions in federal money that pays for 
extra teaching assistants and classroom materials in areas with a high 
percentage of families on welfare, said Jeffrey Baarstad, a district spokesman. 
 
</P>
<P>
 Because of the increasing demand for funds in California, there is less money 
for area schools that qualify for the aid, Baarstad said. The Port Hueneme 
district had about $300,000 cut from its allotment, he said. The district's 
allotment is more than $1 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
 The layoffs would eliminate the district's teaching assistants who are paid 
with the federal money. 
</P>
<P>
 Other school districts in the county receiving the federal money also have had 
to cope with reductions in funds, said Carol Krabill, president of the Hueneme 
chapter of the California Schools Employees Assn. 
</P>
<P>
 Krabill noted that while both the Rio and Ocean View school districts have had 
cuts, neither has made layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a matter of priorities," Krabill said. "They want to use the money for 
more supplies and revamp the program. They don't want to spend it on people." 
SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</TEXT>
