<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIZUELA PAIR VICTORIOUS IN CITY FINALS; HIGH SCHOOL WRESTLING: BROTHERS FROM 
MONROE HIGH EACH CAPTURE THEIR WEIGHT CLASS; BELL WINS TEAM TITLE AGAIN. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL LAZARUS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 For the second straight year, a brother tandem asserted themselves at the City 
Section wrestling championships. 
</P>
<P>
 Last year, junior twins Fernando and Armando Avila won titles for Chatsworth 
High. 
</P>
<P>
 Saturday, the brothers were at Bell High, but only Fernando Avila successfully 
defended his title. 
</P>
<P>
 Monroe's Jose Brizuela (40-1) defeated Armando Avila (24-3), 6-3, in the 
140-pound final. 
</P>
<P>
 Earlier, Brizuela's younger brother, Alfonso Brizuela (35-3), defeated Josh 
Ramon of El Camino Real to win the 119-pound title. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is something we've been working on for the past year," Alfonso Brizuela 
said. "Since last year, when Jose lost." 
</P>
<P>
 Jose Brizuela, a senior, lost to Armando Avila in the semifinals last year. 
</P>
<P>
 Bell, the Central League champion, won five individual titles and won the team 
title with 185 1/2 points for the second straight year. 
</P>
<P>
 El Camino Real, the Valley League champion, finished second with 163 points 
and won three individual titles. 
</P>
<P>
 The Conquistadores gained most of their points at the lower weights. Andy 
Becker (27-9) was the 103-pound champion, beating George Shabazz of Canoga Park 
on a technical fall in the third period. 
</P>
<P>
 In an unusual match, El Camino Real's Casey Lee (119) won his final when he 
was unable to continue after injuring his shoulder. The injury occurred on a 
potentially dangerous move by Charles Zabala of Bell. 
</P>
<P>
 Rick Ullman (152 pounds) was the third Conquistadore wrestler to win a title. 
</P>
<P>
 "We did as well as could have done," Ullman said. "Everyone did their best but 
Bell was a real strong team." 
</P>
<P>
 Bell and El Camino Real led all schools by qualifying seven wrestlers for the 
finals, and the Conquistadores defeated Bell in two of three head-to-head 
finals matchups, but Bell's lead was just too much. 
</P>
<P>
 Bell clinched the team title when Frank Ordorica won by decision over San 
Fernando's Rene Vasquez, 10-3, at 171 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Bell won the final three weight divisions and 189-pound Jesus Orozco (30-2) 
was named the outstanding wrestler of the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
 Monroe and Canoga Park won two titles each. The Hunters finished third in the 
team standings with 107 points. 
</P>
<P>
 At 130 pounds, Canoga Park's Jose Barahuna (27-1), a defending City champion, 
completed an impressive day by pinning Amade Nyirak (18-12) of Monroe, a 
surprise finalist, in 21 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
 Hadi Jubrail won the second championship for the Hunters, beating Hugo Jordan 
of El Camino Real at 160 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
 San Fernando didn't win any individual titles but gained enough points in the 
preliminary rounds to finish fourth with 101 points. Monroe was fifth with 84 
1/2 points. 
</P>
<P>
 Fernando Avila defeated Eduardo Nochez of El Camino Real, 15-8, at 135 pounds. 
The Chancellors finished sixth with 69 points. 
</P>
<P>
 The winner in each weight class will advance to the State championships in 
Stockton this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
