<HEADLINE>
<P>
SNORER HAULED INTO COURT AS NOISE VIOLATOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A woman who snored so loudly that her next-door neighbor couldn't sleep has 
been hauled into court for violating the city's noise ordinance. 
</P>
<P>
 Sari Zayed, a 30-year-old mother of two, pleaded not guilty last week, but 
must return to court March 25.She faces a $50 fine if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
 Her neighbor, Chris Doherty, complained that he lost sleep because he could 
hear the woman's snoring through their common bedroom wall in the duplex. 
</P>
<P>
 Now Zayed says she's the one who can't sleep. 
</P>
<P>
 "You kind of wonder what's going to happen now," she said. "Am I going to 
snore? Is my husband going to snore? Is this man going to come through the 
wall?" 
</P>
<P>
 Zayed has hired a lawyer and is considering a lawsuit of her own. 
</P>
<P>
 Doherty had complained to her three times before calling police. She tried to 
stop, even tried putting a mattress against the wall to muffle the sound. 
</P>
<P>
 An officer investigated on Jan. 31 and recommended mediation. But Doherty was 
fed up. He demanded that she be awakened and cited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
